Name: egisto.sani
Title: Monumental Sarcophagus
Description:
The main side of this richly decorated monumental sarcophagus depicts the myth of Hippolytus and Phaedra. The mythâs iconography is well known. The young man is carved standing exactly in the center of the composition. He is about to leave for hunting and his horse is near him. Phaedra is sitting on a chair. She wears a short-sleeved chiton and a himation risen on her head and covering her legs . The queen is pining away for his son-in-law. She turns her head to the left towards a servant who, leaning toward her and taking her right arm with a familiar gesture, whispers in her ear words of hope or consolation. An Erote symbolizes the love of Phaedra for Hippolytus.
The old nurse of Phaedra stops the young hunter and gives him the tablets containing the love letter written by the queen. Phaedra doesnât look towards him while the old nurse gives the fatal letter to Hippolytus. A hunting scene is carved in the right corner of the scene.
The sculptor has given to the naked Hippolytus the features of Antinous. A klamis wrapping around the left forearm is thrown over the left shoulder. The left hand holds a spear leaning on the shoulder; the sword attached to a harness going over the right shoulder is hanging on the left side. The right hand, placed at waist height, holds the tablets delivered to him by the nurse. But Hippolytus does not read the message: he turns left towards the old woman depicted by means of singularly individual features. She is looking and speaking towards Hippolytus; her words are accompanied with the gesture of her raised left hand.
The decorations of the friezes, of the lid, of the architectural elements of the sarcophagus are astonishingly rich.

Source: Catalogue Mendel, Tome 1, page 109, Notice 0026

Roman sarcophagus
2nd Century AD
From Tripoli, Lebanon
Istanbul, Archaeological Museum

Name: Alessandra Kocman
Title: Inside the Krak des Chevaliers
Description:
Krak des Chevaliers is a Crusader fortress in Syria and one of the most important preserved medieval military castles in the world. In Arabic, the fortress is called Qal'at al-á¸¤iá¹£n (Arabic: ÙÙØ¹Ø© Ø§ÙØ­ØµÙâ). It is located approximately 40 km west of the city of Homs, close to the border of Lebanon, and is administratively part of the Homs Governorate.

The castle was made a World Heritage Site, along with Qalâat Salah El-Din, in 2006, and is owned by the Syrian government. The fortress is one of the few sites where Crusader art (in the form of frescoes) has been preserved.

The castle is located east of Tripoli, Lebanon, in the Homs Gap, atop a 650-metre-high hill along the only route from Antioch to Beirut and the Mediterranean Sea. It is one of many fortresses that were part of a defensive network along the border of the old Crusader states. The fortress controlled the road to the Mediterranean, and from this base, the Hospitallers could exert some influence over Lake Homs to the east to control the fishing industry and watch for Muslim armies gathering in Syria.

The original fortress at this location had been built in 1031 for the emir of Aleppo.

The original fortress at this location had been built in 1031 for the emir of Aleppo.

Name: JAIRO BD
Title: You Abud? Me Abud!
Description:
In 1926, with two small children and pregnant with my father, my grandmother decided to leave Lebanon and journey to Brazil, in the hopes of leading here a more peaceful and prosperous life. She died 29 years ago and the small family she brought up here gradually lost contact with any relatives who still lived there. I just knew she was born in a small northern village, a few kilometers away from Tripoli. Last week, while talking to a few restaurant employees in Tripoli, one of them asked my full name. To mine and everybody elseâs surprise, he exclaimed: âYou Abud? Me Abud!â

Let me introduce you to Abdel Majid Abud, my long lost cousinâ¦ :)

Ela morreu 29 anos atrÃ¡s, e a pequena famÃ­lia que trouxe atÃ© aqui foi perdendo contato com parentes que ainda vivem por lÃ¡. Eu sÃ³ sabia que ela nasceu em uma pequena vila do norte, a poucos quilÃ³metros de Tripoli. Na semana passada, enquanto conversÃ¡vamos com alguns funcionÃ¡rios de um restaurante em TrÃ­poli, um deles perguntou o meu nome completo. Para minha surpresa e todos demais, ele exclamou: "You Abud? Me Abud! "

Name: Lindsay_NYC
Title: [ 16 ] shooting up close and personal
Description:
Tripoli, Lebanon.

I had SO many photos from today that it was hard to choose just on to represent it in my YIP. I chose this one because it gives you a little bit of the feel of Tripoli but mostly because it shows how much we were shooting people today. I really like that aspect of street photography and no one in this group was shy to walk up to a complete stranger and take their picture. It helped that the people of Tripoli were so open to having their pictures taken and would stand totally natural while six people took their picture at the same time. I only saw a handful of people refuse to have their picture taken today.

Name: Bernardo Ricci Armani PhotographingAround.Me
Title: Tripoli - The Soap Maker
Description:
Tripoli is the largest city in northern Lebanon and the second-largest city in Lebanon. Situated 85 km north of the capital Beirut. In ancient times, it was the center of a Phoenician confederation which included Tyre, Sidon and Arados, hence the name Tripoli, meaning "triple city" in Greek. 

At the end of the 15th century, the governor of Tripoli (Lebanon) Youssef Bek Sayfa established Khan Al Saboun (the hotel of soap traders). This market was finished at the beginning of the 16th century, the last days of the Mamlouks ruling. The manufacture of soap was very popular in Tripoli. There, the market became a trade center where soap was produced and sold. Afterwards, traders of Tripoli began to export their soap to Europe.

At first, those perfumed soaps were offered as gifts in Europe. Therefore, handiwork developed in Tripoli. Due to the ongoing increase of the demand, craftsmen started to consider this job as a real art and wanted to satisfy their product amateurs by manufacturing various forms of more effective good-quality soap. Thatâs how the Arab and occidental countries began to import the soap of Tripoli. 

Nowadays, we find all kinds of soaps in Tripoli: slimming soaps, anti-acne soaps, moisturizing soapsâ¦ Some producers are even turning to exportation more than ever. The raw material used for these kinds of soap is olive oil. The Tripoli soap is also composed of: honey, essential oils, natural aromatic raw materials like: flowers, petals, herbsâ¦ The soaps are dried in the sun, in a dry atmosphere: this allows the evaporation of water that served to mix the different ingredients.
The drying operation lasts for almost three months. As water evaporates, a thin white layer appears on the soap surface: it is the soda that comes from the sea salts. 

The craftsman brushes the soap very carefully with his hand until the powder trace is entirely eliminated.
